<br>
“Vile one, you haven’t the faintest idea of what  you speak. You talk of Conflict? And neutrality being for the weak? Let me educate you, foolish child of Hate. The conflict, the battle, the killing, these do not discriminate between good and evil. The most righteous cleric of Tunare and the most despicable thief in the service of Innoruuk can both be brought low by a sword through their abdomen, or their neck or mouth if a quick kill is desired.<br>
<br>
“Some of you, you have the choice of whom to serve, of what cause you choose to defend with your life. But there are others of us who do not have such luxuries. We are commanded to seek out the battle and give ourselves to it. This order does not come from an earthly commander, but from a fire that burns in our hearts and cannot be extinguished.  We may attempt to give our lives to another cause” – <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> at this, the elf sighed</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> – “but find that in the end, we cannot change from how the gods originally made us. And…”<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> At this, the elf was brought up short by the sounds of fighting off in the fields. His interest aroused, he ducked low among the tall grass and sneaked quietly up to the combatants. It seemed that a young wood elf, far away from home, had fallen afoul of a troll lurking in the swamps nearby. Aradil watched the fight with interest, observing the skill with which the elf avoided the heavy blows from the troll’s club. But the elf tripped on the root of a nearby tree, and went down to the ground. Seizing the moment, the troll swung his club down toward the elf’s head…<br>
<br>
…and the elf saw Aradil, hiding in the grass. Though his fate was already decided, a plea for help went out from the young elf’s eyes. A brief sigh escaped Aradil’s lips…<br>
<br>
 …and the club crushed the elf’s skull, and the eyes were no more. The troll raised his head and howled to the sky, proclaiming his victory to whatever vile god he worshipped.  He bent down to feast upon his fallen foe.<br>
<br>
But Aradil had crept up behind the troll while the monster gloated, and within moments, the troll slumped down on top of the elf’s corpse. The warrior wiped the green blood off on the troll’s rags, and then sheathed it.<br>
<br>
As Aradil continued his journey, his thoughts continued as well.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
“I have no love for the monsters in the swamps, or the dark skinned murderers in their underground home. But if death had not come here for this elf, death would have came later, perhaps when people depended on his strength and only found out that he was weak when it was too late.” <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> He sighed again. <br>
<br>
He left the bodies where they lay in the grass.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->  <br>
